<div id="review_241252844" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/241252844" />
    <a title="Margaret Langstaff" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4062463-margaret-langstaff"><img alt="Margaret Langstaff" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442519721p2/4062463.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/241252844?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Margaret Langstaff" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Margaret Langstaff" href="/user/show/4062463-margaret-langstaff">Margaret Langstaff</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer241252844" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1978717509302377506">In an almost uncanny intuitive way this writer grabs the whole Amelia Earhart lalapalooza --mystery, glamor, publicity whirlwind -- and turns it upside down, rendering a surprisingly convincing intimate voice, fictional surely, but quite an accomplishment nevertheless, of a lonely misunderstood woman who made her living by creating then being a legend. I am over familiar with the facts of Earhart&apos;s life, have been close friends with members of her family descendants for 30 yrs.,know the inside s</span>
  <span id="freeText1978717509302377506" style="display:none">In an almost uncanny intuitive way this writer grabs the whole Amelia Earhart lalapalooza --mystery, glamor, publicity whirlwind -- and turns it upside down, rendering a surprisingly convincing intimate voice, fictional surely, but quite an accomplishment nevertheless, of a lonely misunderstood woman who made her living by creating then being a legend. I am over familiar with the facts of Earhart's life, have been close friends with members of her family descendants for 30 yrs.,know the inside skinny-gossip-beefs, along with all the public mythologizing, yet this short novel pierced through all of that,the public persona and the "my great grandmama," and I heard a real woman's voice coming through in the way the novel is written, a unique melancholy yet innocent voice, examining her own sad life and times in an unforgettably moving way. This is where art triumphs over life and delivers transcendence and meaning. A memoir and biography cannot do that, rooted as they must be in the facts, the quotidian, the documented-verifiable elements of a person's walk through time. Ole Aristotle was right. Only fiction and poetry, though he called it "tragedy," written with skill and inspiration, can deliver the essence and the truth of a life minus the irrelevant distractions.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1978717509302377506" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

