    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_107600313" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/107600313" />
    <a title="Emily" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/75633-emily"><img alt="Emily" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1250434029p2/75633.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/107600313?book_show_action=true">Jun 17, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emily" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emily" href="/user/show/75633-emily">Emily</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/75633-emily?shelf=own">own</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer107600313" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16286591051781192">The first third of this novel had me rolling my eyes. The main story picks up during the preparations for Amelia Earhart&apos;s final trip and it is mostly told from her point of view. And it is a depressed point of view. From what I&apos;ve read about Amelia Earhart, she was tough, not moody. I was kind of miffed that the author would attempt to make her into some kind of angsty, suicidal Virginia Woolf-like character.<br/><br/>Once the plane took off though, I could barely put the book down since from that point </span>
  <span id="freeText16286591051781192" style="display:none">The first third of this novel had me rolling my eyes. The main story picks up during the preparations for Amelia Earhart's final trip and it is mostly told from her point of view. And it is a depressed point of view. From what I've read about Amelia Earhart, she was tough, not moody. I was kind of miffed that the author would attempt to make her into some kind of angsty, suicidal Virginia Woolf-like character.<br /><br />Once the plane took off though, I could barely put the book down since from that point on the story took on more and more elements of fantasy and I was totally sucked into Amelia's character. She was strong and independent the whole way through the rest of the book and in Part 2 especially, her reactions to what was happening around her are completely riveting.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16286591051781192" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

